<section xml:id="sec-limits-and-differentiation">
  <title>Limits and differentiation</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Connect derivatives to limits by interpreting slope as a limiting ratio of changes.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use limit reasoning to justify core differentiation rules and identify indeterminate forms.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify situations where a function fails to be differentiable.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Limit definition of a derivative:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>f'(a) \amp = \limit{x\to a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}</mrow>
        <mrow>f'(x) \amp = \limit{h\to 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Prove Power Rule, Product Rule
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>0/0</m> as an indeterminate form
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Ways in which a function can fail to be differentiable, using <m>|x|</m> as the example:
        <me>
          \dv{x}|x|=\frac{|x|}{x}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Role of differentials as changes along the tangent line
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
